06477nam a22013455i 9780228018384DE-B159720240306123113.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20232023xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97802280183847 a10.1515/97802280183842doi  a(DE-B1597)658171  a(OCoLC)1357155014  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aRJ103.F8b.V468 2023 7aHIS0130002bisacsh04a362.1984009432231 aVentura, Gal, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHush Little Baby :bThe Invention of Infant Sleep in Modern France /cGal Ventura. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2023] 4c©2023  a1 online resource :b65 illustrations, colour insert  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tSleeping Like a Baby? -- tPhysicians -- tSleep and the Laws of Nature: Liberty and Disarray -- tSleep and the Laws of Habit: Regulation and Control -- tMothers -- tThe Institution of Motherhood: Vigilance and Bliss -- tAmbivalent Mothering: Tediousness and Depression -- tEntrepreneurs -- tThe Commodification of Sleep: Space, Clothing, and Toys -- tThe Cradle of Life: Hygiene and Social Standing -- tSleepless Babies Epidemic: Contemporary Trends and Tactics -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the nineteenth century France became fixated on infant sleep. Pictures of sleeping babies proliferated in paintings, posters, and advertisements for cradles and toys. Childcare manuals and medical writings insisted on the importance of sleep as a measure of a child’s future health and vigour. Infant sleep was transformed from an unremarkable event to a precarious stage of life that demanded monitoring, support, and, above all, the constant presence and attention of mothers. Hush Little Baby uncovers the cultural, medical, and economic forces that came to shape Western ideas about infants’ sleeping patterns, rituals, and settings. By the mid-nineteenth century doctors were advising that infant sleep should be carefully controlled by caregivers according to medical guidelines, and that to do otherwise would risk compromising a child’s development. A sleeping baby was seen as the sign of a good mother – an idea that was reinforced through countless pictures of mothers watching vigilantly over their sleeping children, even as the reality of postpartum depression was known to doctors. The medical advice literature also helped to create a commercial infant industry, encouraging the production of clothing, bedding, cradles, and accessories designed to foster sleep, and providing new ways for families to demonstrate social status. In Hush Little Baby Gal Ventura shows how these images and ideas about babies’ sleep created many of the standards and expectations that keep parents awake today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aInfantsxCarezFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aInfantsxCarezFrance. 0aInfantsxSleepzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aInfantsxSleepzFrance. 0aInfants' supplies industryzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aInfants' supplies industryzFrancexHistory. 0aMotherhoodzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aMotherhoodzFrancexHistory. 0aSleeping customszFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aSleeping customszFrancexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aAlfred Stevens.  aArt.  aAvangard.  aBabies.  aBassinets.  aBed.  aBerthe Morisot.  aBreastFeeding.  aClaude Monet.  aClothing.  aCradles.  aCribs.  aCry-It-Out.  aCunsumerism.  aDemedicalization.  aDepartment.  aDepopulation.  aDepression.  aDesign.  aDoctors.  aDoll.  aEdgar Degas.  aFrance.  aFrench.  aGrand.  aH